                "href": "https://www.daryllswer.com/wp-json/wp/v2/posts/5136",
                "post_type": "post"
              }
            ]
          },
          "author": 0,
          "author_avatar_urls": {
            "24": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/2379641e73e3046a64e070f0891b72e055f5be1e1f99661775c76fee0172baa2?s=24&r=g",
            "48": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/2379641e73e3046a64e070f0891b72e055f5be1e1f99661775c76fee0172baa2?s=48&r=g",
            "96": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/2379641e73e3046a64e070f0891b72e055f5be1e1f99661775c76fee0172baa2?s=96&r=g"
          },
          "author_name": "Tristan Velloza Kildaire",
          "author_url": "https://deavmi.assigned.network",
          "content": {
            "rendered": "<p>I am able to get ICMPv6 packets in with this setup and have confirmed it (I exec&#8217;d into the container and then tcpdump&#8217;d).</p>\n<p>However, any port-based protocols like TCP and UDP seem to fail when sent form that same remote host (several hops away); only pinging works it seems.</p>\n<p>Any ideas? I know the container is bound correctly and I can reach 9from the container machine) the container&#8217;s port 3000. But trying to do so remotely doesn&#8217;t work.</p>\n<p>I have tried both with iptables6 set to `true` and `false`.</p>\n<p>My network config is here: <a href=\"https://github.com/deavmi/docker/blob/master/nodes/services/networks.yml#L26\" rel=\"nofollow ugc\">https://github.com/deavmi/docker/blob/master/nodes/services/networks.yml#L26</a><br />\nAnd the service, `gitea_old`, here: <a href=\"https://github.com/deavmi/docker/blob/master/nodes/services/git.yml#L23\" rel=\"nofollow ugc\">https://github.com/deavmi/docker/blob/master/nodes/services/git.yml#L23</a></p>\n"
          },
          "date": "2025-10-15T19:35:44",
          "id": 1854,
          "link": "https://www.daryllswer.com/how-to-configure-routed-ipv6-in-docker/#comment-1854",
          "parent": 0,
          "type": "comment"
        },
